content.problemStatement:
In this lesson, we'll learn how to remove elements from an ArrayList using two methods: `remove(int index)` and `remove(value)`.



1. **`remove(int index)`** - Removes the element at the specified position
2. `remove(value)` - Removes the first occurrence of the specified value

---

**Example**
```java
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList fruits = new ArrayList<>();

        // Adding elements to the ArrayList
        fruits.add("Apple");   // index 0
        fruits.add("Banana");  // index 1
        fruits.add("Mango");   // index 2
        fruits.add("Banana");  // index 3 (duplicate to show value-based removal)

        System.out.println("Original list: " + fruits); // [Apple, Banana, Mango, Banana]

        // 1. remove(int index) - Removes element at the specified position
        fruits.remove(0); // Removes "Apple" at index 0
        // Important Note: After removal, elements shift left. Now "Banana" is at index 0.

        System.out.println("After remove(0): " + fruits); // [Banana, Mango, Banana]

        // 2. remove(Object value) - Removes the first occurrence of the specified value
        fruits.remove("Banana"); // Removes the first "Banana"
        // Important Note: Only the first match is removed. Remaining "Banana" still exists.

        System.out.println("After remove(\"Banana\"): " + fruits); // [Mango, Banana]

        // Important Note: 
        // - If index is invalid (like remove(10)), it throws IndexOutOfBoundsException.
        // - If value doesn’t exist, remove(value) returns false and does nothing.
    }
}
```

